If you want to expand to a broader market of AI automations, it's essential to differentiate your product from competitors like IFTTT. Here are a few suggestions to help you achieve that:

Identify gaps in the market: Analyze IFTTT's offering and identify areas where your product can provide unique and valuable AI automations that are not currently being offered. You can conduct market research to find out what users want and need that IFTTT does not provide.

Focus on a specific niche: Instead of trying to compete with IFTTT across the board, you can focus on a specific niche or industry that requires AI automations. For example, you could specialize in automations for the healthcare industry or educational institutions.

Emphasize your unique value proposition: Highlight the unique value proposition that your product offers, such as superior customization, advanced functionality, or better user experience. Make sure your messaging and marketing materials reflect this differentiation.

Build partnerships: Consider partnering with other companies or platforms to integrate your AI automation offerings with theirs. This can help expand your reach and bring your product to a wider audience.

Innovate: Continuously improve your product and stay up to date with the latest AI automation technologies and trends. Look for ways to innovate and create new and unique offerings that can set you apart from IFTTT and other competitors.

Remember, differentiation is key to standing out in a crowded market. By focusing on what makes your product unique and valuable, you can create a successful business that can compete with even the biggest players in the industry.

This would allow us to grow into the brand recognizable portion in a similar way to notion, google, apple, etc... A domain name doesn't need to be related to our product in the end. It doesn't need to feel sciency (it needs to appeal to the mass market). Think square.com, wix.com, slate.ai, amazon.com, etc... All of these countless examples don't really have any relationship back to the original product but they're good anyways. I do like autom.ai but I'm not even sure if we'll be able to get it at this point in time and so far it feels like I'm the only one who like it. I can give you all the reasons I don't like diffraction.ai but in reality it all boils down to it being too long in my mind. When you think of Google you think of Google not Alphabet Inc.
